            <fr:anchor>19270</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LW</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00LW.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Finite and infinite sets">Finite and infinite sets</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Now that we have learned about <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijections</fr:link>, we are ready to replace our intuitive/informal understanding of finite sets and finite cardinality with a formal one.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7619</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LX</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00LX.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Finite set">Finite set</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>finite</fr:strong></fr:em> or have <fr:em><fr:strong>finite cardinality</fr:strong></fr:em> when it is <fr:link href="jms-00L0.xml" title="Isomorphic sets" addr="jms-00L0" type="local">isomorphic</fr:link> to a set of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>; in this case, we therefore have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=n]]></fr:tex>. (Recall that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the standard <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-element</html:span> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{i\in \mathbb {N}\,\middle \vert \,0\leq  i < n\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.)</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>There are many identities that relate set-theoretic operations on <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite sets</fr:link> to arithmetic operations on their cardinalities. We will illustrate a few of them here.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7622</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LY</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00LY.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Cardinality of the cartesian product">Cardinality of the cartesian product</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We can prove this from a combinatoric point of view.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7620</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6067</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6067.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>To choose a pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we first choose an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and we second choose an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. There are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> possibilities for the first choice and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> possibilities for the second choice; as these choices are independent, we simply have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> choices in total.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We can also prove this isomorphism more formally by means of a specific bijection.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7621</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6068</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6068.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of the cartesian product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of cells in table or matrix with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> columns and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> rows — and then an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j\in {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the coordinate of a given cell. Naturally, the total number of cells would be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex>, but we can prove this formally by constructing the function that takes a coordinate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to its absolute index in the counting of cells from left to right and top to bottom:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \begin {aligned}
   I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\
   I{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}} &= m\cdot  j + i
  \end {aligned}
 ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We do need to check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}< m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i<m]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j<n]]></fr:tex>. The maximimum value of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is naturally <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I{\mathopen {}\left (m-1,n-1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  I{\mathopen {}\left (m-1,n-1\right )\mathclose {}} &= m\cdot {\mathopen {}\left (n-1\right )\mathclose {}} + {\mathopen {}\left (m-1\right )\mathclose {}}
  \\
  &=
  m\cdot  n - m + m - 1
  \\
  &=
  m\cdot  n - 1
  \\
  &< m\cdot  n
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex><fr:p>The inverse function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I^{-1}\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> takes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i<m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> to the pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\operatorname {rem}{\mathopen {}\left (i,m\right )\mathclose {}}, \operatorname {quo}{\mathopen {}\left (i,m\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7624</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LZ</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00LZ.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Cardinality of the disjoint sum">Cardinality of the disjoint sum</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7623</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6069</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6069.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates into two strips of cells, the first of which has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells and the second of which has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> cells. Conversely, we can think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates a single strip of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m+n]]></fr:tex> cells. A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> could then be thought of as witnessing a method to lay out the two strips in serial; we will define such a function and show that it is a bijection.</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \begin {aligned}
   I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\
   I{\mathopen {}\left (0,i<m\right )\mathclose {}} &= i\\
   I{\mathopen {}\left (1,j<n\right )\mathclose {}} &= m+j
  \end {aligned}
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>The function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> places a cell from the first strip sequentially after the first <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells of the serialised strip. The inverse can be defined as follows:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  I{\mathopen {}\left (k\right )\mathclose {}} =
  \begin {cases}
   {\mathopen {}\left (0,k\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k < m\\
   {\mathopen {}\left (1,k-m\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k \geq  m
  \end {cases}
 ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7625</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00M1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00M1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Infinite set">Infinite set</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>infinite</fr:strong></fr:em> when it is not <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite</fr:link> in the sense of <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00LX" /></fr:link>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>The basic axioms of set theory that we have learned in this course so far do not in fact guarantee the existence of any <fr:link href="jms-00M1.xml" title="Infinite set" addr="jms-00M1" type="local">infinite sets</fr:link>. For this reason, one usually adds the <fr:link href="jms-00M1.xml" title="Infinite set" addr="jms-00M1" type="local">axiom of infinity</fr:link> below to set theory.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7626</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00M0</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00M0.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="The axiom of infinity">The axiom of infinity</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Axiom</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The natural numbers form a set.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" hidden-when-empty="true">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:anchor>19276</fr:anchor>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>19272</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016H</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016H.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Alphabet">Alphabet</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:em><fr:strong>alphabet</fr:strong></fr:em> is specified by giving a <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite set</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> whose elements are called <fr:em>symbols</fr:em>. Any <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite set</fr:link> can serve as an alphabet as far as we are concerned.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
              <fr:contributor>
                <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
              </fr:contributor>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>1</fr:month>
              <fr:day>30</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>19273</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00N4</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00N4.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Counting injections between finite sets">Counting <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injections</fr:link> between <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite sets</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite sets</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we can describe number of <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injections</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \mathord {\#}{\mathrm {Inj}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}} =
 \begin {cases}
  {\mathord {\#}{B}\choose \mathord {\#}{A}}\cdot  {\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}\right )\mathclose {}}! &\text {when } \mathord {\#}{A}\leq  \mathord {\#}{B}
  \\
  0 &\text {otherwise}
 \end {cases}
]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7319</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6082</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6082.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>An <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> associates no more than one <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> to the same <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>as each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  U]]></fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that is in <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{B}\choose  \mathord {\#}{A}]]></fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:link href="jms-00KT.xml" title="Counting bijections between finite sets" addr="jms-00KT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KT" /></fr:link> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}!\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
              <fr:contributor>
                <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
              </fr:contributor>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>1</fr:month>
              <fr:day>28</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>19274</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LW</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00LW.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Finite and infinite sets">Finite and infinite sets</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Now that we have learned about <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijections</fr:link>, we are ready to replace our intuitive/informal understanding of finite sets and finite cardinality with a formal one.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7619</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LX</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00LX.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Finite set">Finite set</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>finite</fr:strong></fr:em> or have <fr:em><fr:strong>finite cardinality</fr:strong></fr:em> when it is <fr:link href="jms-00L0.xml" title="Isomorphic sets" addr="jms-00L0" type="local">isomorphic</fr:link> to a set of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>; in this case, we therefore have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=n]]></fr:tex>. (Recall that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the standard <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-element</html:span> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{i\in \mathbb {N}\,\middle \vert \,0\leq  i < n\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.)</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>There are many identities that relate set-theoretic operations on <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite sets</fr:link> to arithmetic operations on their cardinalities. We will illustrate a few of them here.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7622</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LY</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00LY.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Cardinality of the cartesian product">Cardinality of the cartesian product</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We can prove this from a combinatoric point of view.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7620</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6067</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6067.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>To choose a pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we first choose an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and we second choose an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. There are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> possibilities for the first choice and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> possibilities for the second choice; as these choices are independent, we simply have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> choices in total.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We can also prove this isomorphism more formally by means of a specific bijection.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7621</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6068</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6068.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of the cartesian product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of cells in table or matrix with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> columns and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> rows — and then an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j\in {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is the coordinate of a given cell. Naturally, the total number of cells would be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex>, but we can prove this formally by constructing the function that takes a coordinate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to its absolute index in the counting of cells from left to right and top to bottom:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \begin {aligned}
   I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\
   I{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}} &= m\cdot  j + i
  \end {aligned}
 ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We do need to check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I{\mathopen {}\left (i,j\right )\mathclose {}}< m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i<m]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j<n]]></fr:tex>. The maximimum value of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is naturally <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I{\mathopen {}\left (m-1,n-1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  I{\mathopen {}\left (m-1,n-1\right )\mathclose {}} &= m\cdot {\mathopen {}\left (n-1\right )\mathclose {}} + {\mathopen {}\left (m-1\right )\mathclose {}}
  \\
  &=
  m\cdot  n - m + m - 1
  \\
  &=
  m\cdot  n - 1
  \\
  &< m\cdot  n
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex><fr:p>The inverse function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I^{-1}\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\cdot  n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}\times {\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> takes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i<m\cdot  n]]></fr:tex> to the pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\operatorname {rem}{\mathopen {}\left (i,m\right )\mathclose {}}, \operatorname {quo}{\mathopen {}\left (i,m\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7624</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00LZ</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00LZ.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Cardinality of the disjoint sum">Cardinality of the disjoint sum</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \cong  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>28</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7623</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6069</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6069.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We can think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates into two strips of cells, the first of which has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells and the second of which has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> cells. Conversely, we can think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> as the set of coordinates a single strip of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m+n]]></fr:tex> cells. A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> could then be thought of as witnessing a method to lay out the two strips in serial; we will define such a function and show that it is a bijection.</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \begin {aligned}
   I &\colon {\mathopen {}\left  [m\right  ]\mathclose {}}+{\mathopen {}\left  [n\right  ]\mathclose {}} \to  {\mathopen {}\left  [m+n\right  ]\mathclose {}}\\
   I{\mathopen {}\left (0,i<m\right )\mathclose {}} &= i\\
   I{\mathopen {}\left (1,j<n\right )\mathclose {}} &= m+j
  \end {aligned}
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>The function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> places a cell from the first strip sequentially after the first <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> cells of the serialised strip. The inverse can be defined as follows:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  I{\mathopen {}\left (k\right )\mathclose {}} =
  \begin {cases}
   {\mathopen {}\left (0,k\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k < m\\
   {\mathopen {}\left (1,k-m\right )\mathclose {}} &\text {when } k \geq  m
  \end {cases}
 ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7625</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00M1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00M1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Infinite set">Infinite set</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>infinite</fr:strong></fr:em> when it is not <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite</fr:link> in the sense of <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00LX" /></fr:link>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>The basic axioms of set theory that we have learned in this course so far do not in fact guarantee the existence of any <fr:link href="jms-00M1.xml" title="Infinite set" addr="jms-00M1" type="local">infinite sets</fr:link>. For this reason, one usually adds the <fr:link href="jms-00M1.xml" title="Infinite set" addr="jms-00M1" type="local">axiom of infinity</fr:link> below to set theory.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7626</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00M0</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00M0.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="The axiom of infinity">The axiom of infinity</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Axiom</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The natural numbers form a set.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
